-depth interviews with mothers with severe mental health problems; · identifies weaknesses in interprofessional coordination in this area of work; · suggests a new model for work with families where mental health problems and child protection concerns co-exist. All those involved in child protection or mental health work with families will find this book a stimulating read. This book will be of interest to practitioners, managers and policy makers as well as students studying health and social care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChild welfarezGreat Britain. 0aMental health serviceszGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aHolden, Sue, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPenhale, Bridget, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRiordan, Denise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z978311119621340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847425799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847425799/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles